<paragraph blockId="15.[811,1420,1321,1758]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,1398,1422]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">IDentificAtion.</emphasis>
This species was detected in all periods, mostly by voice. It was rarely seen but frequently heard. This species was observed making short flights and discreet landings among aquatic macrophytes (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kunth" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Pontederiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Commelinales" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Pontederiaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[993,1144,1532,1556]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Least Bittern WA" baseAuthorityName="Gmelin" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[1164,1352,1532,1556]" class="Aves" family="Ardeidae" genus="Ixobrychus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pelecaniformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis box="[1164,1352,1532,1556]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Ixobrychus exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a characteristic voice and vocalises frequently. This species is a small, reddish-brown bittern, with two white stripes on the back. The male has a black cap and back, with yellowish stripes on the throat, while the female has a brown cap and back, with the darkest bands on the neck (Martínez-Vilata et al. 2018).
</paragraph>
